ork</a><span> Post</span></em><span>. Many thanks to Rikki Schlott for her =
thoughtful questions, and photographer John Nguyen for the images. Here=E2=
=80=99s a portion:</span></p><blockquote><p><strong>You argue that educated=
 people tend to overemphasize education as a fix-all for underprivileged ki=
ds. Why is that?</strong></p><p>People involved in policy and shaping cultu=
re focus on education as the primary means of upward social mobility.</p><p=
>One of the points I try to make in the book is that yes, education is impo=
rtant.</p><p>It worked for me.</p><p>But it doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily wor=
k for everyone.</p><p>Even though I was always academically inclined, the l=
evel of disorder in my life was weighing me down so much that I wasn=E2=80=
=99t in a position to fully exploit my own capabilities.</p><p>I=E2=80=99d =
like us to focus more on what happens before age 18 than after.</p><p>We=E2=
=80=99re so focused on, =E2=80=98Ok, they graduate high school. Do they go =
to college or not? And do they graduate from college?=E2=80=99 I argue that=
, through childhood and adolescence, we have to focus more on, =E2=80=98Are=
 these kids being looked out for? Are they being nurtured? Do they have thi=
s sort of security and adequate care in order for them to achieve the thing=
s that we would like them to achieve?=E2=80=99</p><p>[=E2=80=A6]</p><p><str=
ong>How do you think we can work towards closing the gap between the intell=
ectual elite class and the rest of the public?</strong></p><p>We should be =
skeptical of the people who claim to speak on behalf of these communities.<=
/p><p>Instead of looking to self proclaimed leaders of various marginalized=
 and dispossessed groups, we need to actually ask those groups themselves.<=
/p><p>It=E2=80=99s worth collecting data, looking at surveys, speaking with=
 people =E2=80=94 not just community leaders and activists who have their o=
wn agendas.</p><p>I saw this at Yale where someone who shares the character=
istics of a historically mistreated group would claim to speak on behalf of=
 them, but they had very little in common with them other than the way that=
 they looked.</p><p>I want people to be a bit more skeptical of the self-pr=
oclaimed activist leaders who could be trying to push an agenda, trying to =
elicit sympathy, and trying to exploit people=E2=80=99s concerns</p></block=
quote><p><span>Read the whole thing </span><a href=3D"https://nypost.com/20=
24/02/17/us-news/foster-kid-who-went-to-yale-says-family-trumps-college/" r=
el=3D"">here</a><span>. </span></p><p>Just a note that the article states t=
hat I attended Yale =E2=80=9Cvia their ROTC program,=E2=80=9D which is inco=
rrect. I attended Yale via the GI Bill, which is a separate thing. ROTC (Re=
serve Officers' Training Corps) is a program for college students who gradu=
ate and then go on to serve as military officers. In contrast, the GI Bill =
covers college expenses for veterans who have already served and received h=
onorable discharges from their duties. </p><p><span>To be clear, as </span>=
<a href=3D"https://www.robkhenderson.com/p/youre-probably-not-the-person-im=
" rel=3D"">I=E2=80=99ve written before</a><span>, I=E2=80=99m well aware th=
at there are situations in which divorce makes sense. Abuse, mistreatment, =
truly irreconcilable differences, and so on. Most divorces, though, are the=
 </span><a href=3D"https://x.com/robkhenderson/status/1705137444994068771?s=
=3D20" rel=3D"">result</a><span> of low-conflict disputes. And most single =
parent families are not the result of divorce, but </span><a href=3D"https:=
//www.robkhenderson.com/p/no-one-expects-young-men-to-do-anything" rel=3D""=
>rather</a><span> deadbeat dads. People say we shouldn=E2=80=99t shame sing=
le moms, that they are doing the best they can. I generally agree. I was, f=
or a time, raised by a single mother. I am perfectly at ease, though, with =
saying we can shame absentee fathers.</span></p><div><hr></div><h3 class=3D=
